## Turning the Analysis Into the Official Record

Day 29 introduced FIPS 199 and worked through the impact level reasoning for each security objective. Day 35 added the information type analysis that provides the evidentiary basis for those ratings. Day 43 produced the formal system description. Today, Task C-2 assembles those pieces into the official security categorization document — the formal record that the Authorizing Official reviews, approves, and relies on as the foundation for the entire authorization decision.

This matters because the categorization is not just an analytical conclusion — it is an organizational commitment. When the AO reviews and approves the categorization, they are agreeing that OpenMRS should be treated as a High-impact system, that the High baseline from NIST SP 800-53B applies, and that the assessment and authorization rigor appropriate for a High-impact system will be applied. That commitment drives resources, timelines, and scope for everything that follows.

I also want to be transparent about something: the original version of today's content categorized OpenMRS as Moderate. After working through the detailed FIPS 199 analysis on Day 29 and the information type classification on Day 35, I am confident the correct categorization for an EHR handling ePHI as the sole clinical record system is High across all three security objectives. Today's write-up explains that reasoning fully so the categorization can be defended to anyone who reviews it.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task C-2 requires the organization to document the security categorization using FIPS 199 standards, have the categorization reviewed by the system owner and other relevant organizational officials, and register the categorization with the appropriate organizational officials. The output is the formal categorization statement that becomes part of the System Security Plan.

FIPS 200 then maps the categorization to the minimum security requirements — a Moderate categorization triggers the Moderate baseline from NIST SP 800-53B; a High categorization triggers the High baseline. The difference is substantial: the High baseline includes significantly more controls and more stringent implementation requirements across multiple control families.

Getting the categorization right is therefore not a bureaucratic formality. An under-categorization that produces Moderate when High is appropriate means the security program is built on an inadequate control set — a gap that may not be discovered until an assessment or an incident.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clicked most clearly today is the difference between a provisional impact rating and an adjusted impact rating — and why the adjustment process matters for healthcare systems specifically.

NIST SP 800-60 provides provisional impact ratings for information types — starting points based on the typical sensitivity of each type. For health information, the provisional ratings in SP 800-60 were developed for a federal government context and often land at Moderate. But the FIPS 199 process explicitly requires organizations to review provisional ratings and adjust them based on their specific operational context.

For a direct patient care setting — a clinic where ePHI is used in real-time clinical decision-making, where integrity failures can cause direct patient harm, and where the system is the sole EHR with no paper backup — the adjustments to High across all three objectives are clearly warranted. The provisional Moderate is a starting point for the analysis, not the conclusion.

This is a meaningful distinction because organizations that apply provisional ratings without adjustment may systematically under-categorize healthcare systems — producing Moderate categorizations for systems that genuinely warrant High. The resulting control baselines are inadequate, and the security program is built on a false foundation.

