## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While finalizing today's categorization work I returned to the **2022 CommonSpirit Health ransomware attack** — one of the largest healthcare cybersecurity incidents in recent US history. CommonSpirit, one of the largest nonprofit health systems in the US, experienced a ransomware attack that affected hundreds of facilities across multiple states. EHR systems were taken offline, elective procedures were canceled, and patients at some facilities were diverted to other hospitals.

Post-incident reporting included accounts of specific patient harm — a patient at one CommonSpirit facility received a tenfold overdose of a pain medication because the nurse could not access the correct dosage information in the EHR during the outage and relied on a manual calculation that contained an error.

That case is a direct real-world illustration of what High availability and High integrity impact mean in a healthcare EHR context. The availability failure — the EHR going offline — created the conditions for an integrity-adjacent failure — the inability to access accurate dosage information leading to a medication error. The patient safety consequence was direct and documented.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, the High availability categorization is not a theoretical concern about operational inconvenience. It reflects the documented reality that EHR unavailability in clinical settings creates conditions for patient harm. That is a High impact outcome and it belongs in the categorization record.

