## What I Am Still Thinking About

One question the categorization process raised for me: how should categorization change if MyClinic implements functional downtime procedures and tested paper backup processes?

The availability categorization at High is partly driven by the absence of downtime procedures (V-015 from the vulnerability inventory) and untested backups (V-014). If those gaps are remediated — if MyClinic implements and tests comprehensive clinical downtime procedures — the availability impact of a temporary outage becomes more manageable. An organization with tested paper backup processes and trained staff can sustain clinical operations during an EHR outage without the same severity of patient safety risk.

In that scenario, the availability impact might be defensibly rated Moderate — acknowledging that outages are disruptive but that clinical operations can continue safely. The overall system categorization would still be High due to confidentiality and integrity, but the availability dimension would reflect the improved resilience.

This illustrates an important GRC principle: security categorization is not permanent. As the security posture improves and operational resilience grows, it is appropriate to revisit the categorization and document whether adjusted ratings are warranted. The categorization should reflect the actual risk — not a frozen snapshot from the initial authorization.

